{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486916"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:49:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"207"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/207"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.1,0.14,0.64,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"207"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81307"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/207"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"207"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66649"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"134"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43788"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81307"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of epigastric pain. The pain typically occurs after meals and wakes him in the early hours of the morning. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe initially tried over-the-counter antacids which provided brief relief. He then used pantoprazole for three weeks but stopped one month ago due to lack of effect. For the past month, he has only used occasional antacids. He maintains a good appetite with stable weight and reports no other gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Complete blood count, liver function tests, and renal function are all within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Substitute esomeprazole for pantoprazole","Double the dose of pantoprazole","Gastroscopy with biopsy","Urea breath test","Continue current management"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with typical symptoms of peptic ulcer disease, with post-prandial and nocturnal epigastric pain unresponsive to proton pump inhibitor (PPI) therapy. The poor response to PPI suggests underlying \u003Cem\u003EHelicobacter pylori\u003C/em\u003E infection, which should be investigated before adjusting medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrea breath test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step as it is non-invasive, highly accurate (sensitivity and specificity \u0026gt;95%), and cost-effective. The patient has already been off PPIs for one month, meeting the requirement to stop acid suppression for 1-2 weeks before testing to avoid false negatives.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubstituting esomeprazole\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Efor pantoprazole \u003C/strong\u003Eis unlikely to be effective as both medications have similar efficacy, and the underlying cause of PPI failure needs to be addressed first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoubling the dose of pantoprazole\u003C/strong\u003E without investigating for \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Ewould not address the potential underlying cause of treatment failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroscopy with biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E would be overly invasive as the first investigation in a young patient with no red flag symptoms (such as weight loss, early satiety, or anaemia) and no risk factors for gastric cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue current management\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as the patient\u0027s symptoms are significantly affecting his quality of life and have not responded to initial therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The urea breath test is the preferred non-invasive test for Helicobacter pylori with sensitivity and specificity \u003E95%.","Proton pump inhibitors must be stopped 1-2 weeks before H. pylori testing to avoid false negative results.","Young patients with dyspepsia and no red flags should have H. pylori testing before endoscopy."],"references":["Crowe SE. Helicobacter pylori infection. NEJM. 2019 March 21; 380: 1158-1165. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMcp1710945"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66649"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"207"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66649"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-25T20:00:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-25T20:00:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"207"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81307"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{